{"id":"2108.10208","submitter":"Florent Capelli","authors":"Florent Capelli, Yann Strozecki","title":"Geometric Amortization of Enumeration Algorithms","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CC cs.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we introduce the technique of geometric amortization for\nenumeration algorithms. This technique can be used to make the delay of\nenumeration algorithms more regular without much overhead on the space it uses.\nMore precisely, we are interested in enumeration algorithms having incremental\nlinear delay, that is, algorithms enumerating a set $A$ of size $K$ such that\nfor every $t \\leq K$, it outputs at least $t$ solutions in time $O(tp)$, where\n$p$ is the incremental delay of the algorithm. While it is folklore that one\ncan transform such an algorithm into an algorithm with delay $O(p)$, the naive\ntransformation may blow the space exponentially. We show that, using geometric\namortization, such an algorithm can be transformed into an algorithm with delay\n$O(p\\log K)$ and $O(s\\log K)$ space, where $s$ is the space used by the\noriginal algorithm.\n  We apply geometric amortization to show that one can trade the delay of\nflashlight search algorithms for their average delay modulo a factor of $O(\\log\nK)$. We illustrate how this tradeoff may be advantageous for the enumeration of\nsolutions of DNF formulas.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 23 Aug 2021 14:47:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-24"}
